  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Planning, or creating or extending the plan, is performed in planning tasks. Planning tasks can be performed by human&#xD;
    performers, but can also be system-automated tasks. Planning can be performed in two “modes”:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Ad-hoc, just by a human case participant whenever an authorized participant sees the need&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        When specified in the plan, human-interactively as well as automatic.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
Ad-hoc planning: &lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        On-the-fly, at any moment a human case worker wants to plan something.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Based on the planning pallet that is globally defined for the case type.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        An ad hoc planning task is not defined in design-time. It is created in “run-time” and inserted in the plan,&#xD;
        on-the-fly.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    “Planned” planning:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        A planning task can be specified in a case model. It may be placed in the plan at runtime or incorporated in a plan&#xD;
        fragment or complex task to occur based on an event or completion of other work.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></mainDescription>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription>
